- Bulk storage tanks (including tank components such as level controls, pressure relief, rupture discs, etc.);
- Piping systems (including piping components such as valves, heat tracing elements, etc.);
- Relief and vent systems and devices for all equipment;
- Hydrocarbon Detection system and components;
- Lightning Protection System and components;
- Fire suppression and protection system;
- Grounding protection systems;
- Ventilation system;
- Emergency shutdown systems;
- Process Logic Control (including monitoring devices and sensors, alarms, and interlocks); and
- Supply, Transfer, and Sump Pumps.

NCFI Polyurethane's procedures for maintaining the mechanical integrity (MI) of its pentane mixture process will include initial mechanical integrity testing, training of maintenance personnel, preventive maintenance inspection/testing, and a system to immediately correct any deficiencies noted.
Hot Work Permit Program
In accordance with the requirements of OSHA's PSM regulations and EPA's RMP regulations, NCFI Polyurethane has developed and implemented a Hot Work Permit Program for all hot work operations conducted on or near its pentane mixture processes.  Permits are required for all such work, whether done by vendor, contractor, or NCFI Polyurethanes personnel, including plant maintenance. 
This program shall cover the following hot work processes:
- Welding and allied processes, not including spot welding or seam welding.
- Heat treating.
- Grinding.
- Thawing pipe.
- Powder-driven fasteners.
- Similar applications producing a spark, flame, or heat.
